paddlesteamer Jul 07 2013
+66 Vote downBookmarkVote up
I would whole-heartedly agree with the collective RYM wisdom that this is one of the greatest albums in rock, and I would also agree with those reviewers who claim that this is long, messy and padded with a fair bit of filler. Yet to complain about the filler is to miss the point of the White Album. John Lennon called it "the son of Sgt. Pepper", and it is interesting to consider what he means in this context. The two albums are as different in approach as you can imagine. Whereas Pepper was meticulously planned and orchestrated, this is chaotic, so I presume what Lennon really meant is that The White Album is a reaction against Pepper- it is as spontaneous, impulsive and sprawling as Pepper was tight and unified. And this album really is an astonishing feat of musical creativity and adventurism. By the time the first side has ended we have swung from the back to the 50s rock of the opener, to the gorgeous pop-psychedelia of Dear Prudence, to the sunny, Nanna-pleasing pop of Ob-La-Di, Ob-La-Da to the poignant lyricism of While My Guitar Gently Weeps- perhaps Harrison's best song- and at last to the disturbing and disturbingly under-rated, Happiness Is a Warm Gun. Even if Wild Honey Pie or Bungalow Bill annoyed the hell out of you along the way, that is still some track list. In the end, I am glad that just let it all hang out. Had they followed Martin's advice and cut it back to a Revolver-like 14 track set, I fear that the delicate Julia or the cryptic Everybody's Got Something to Hide Except Me and My Monkey might have ended up on the cutting room floor. I'd rather have the album the way it is- a testament to a time when the biggest-selling band in the world had a real experimental edge- something that is unimaginable now.
Published
streetmouse Jun 19 2008
+14 Vote downBookmarkVote up
As far back as the very first Beatle release, their albums had a contextual feel. With the release of the singles Penny Lane, and Strawberry Fields, followed by the albums Revolver, Sgt. Pepper, and Magical Mystery Tour, the Fab Four seemed to be uniting the world through a charismatic set of themed albums revolving around the Flower Power movement, psychedelic drugs, and the ability to be able to draw us all together, united in a stance not only against the war in Vietnam, but in the power this new generation had in their hands, to change the course of social and political events. While there were signals of disillusion, and troubles within the band, as found on the George Harrison song Blue Jay Way, I think we all saw this as typical issues any group or family are destined to have, especially when they have worked so closely for so many years.

And the White Album was just as prophetic in its on way. I remember hearing it not only for the first time, but the second, and third time ... and thinking that though the songs were well crafted, there was something lacking. The music seemed disjointed, like light refracted through a prism, with most of the songs more than notably written by single members of the band. Some songs seemed to be pulled or left over from other adventures, leaving me with a shattered, schizophrenic feeling ... there was nothing inter laced, nothing tying the songs together. This feeling was not lost on most fans, yet these were The Beatles, a group who had taken us on a serious journey, collimating in a series of climatic musical ecstasies, the peak of the trip, a feeling I never wanted to leave my body.

But here on the White Album, there was nothing I could warm up to. The 'White Album' felt like the crash, the day after the trip, when the excesses of speed that the LSD had been cut with showed their head, leaving me with an uncomfortable feeling ... one of uncertainty, pending doom, and a disconnection to say the least ... a feeling I just wanted to sleep through, wake up and find that all of the music on this double release made sense.

I had to set this record aside for a very long time, going to places like Vietnam, where the world actually was schizophrenic. And now, nearly forty years later, while I have come to appreciated the songs as a very good grouping of music, I still see the White Album as the light at the end of the tunnel, a tunnel that had once bathed and warmed me in strobing colours, psychedelic sensuality, pleasantly distorted shapes that would bend and ebb, as musical notes, like breezes changed my total perception ... I thought the light at the end of the tunnel would be more this, but then as The Beatles had grown up, so had I, and I was left with the reality that most things are not what they seemed.

+3 Vote downBookmarkVote up
I sometimes lose sight of the fact that the Beatles were first and foremost a rock and roll band and not just acid tinged experimentalists who would rather shoot off their own legs than do something that had been done similarly before. If nothing else then The White Album has allowed me to keep sight of that which I have lost sight of (?? See above). Opening with the bulldozing and relentless rock and roll of Back in the U.S.S.R. this double disc set has plenty more rocking to get through before it has finished with our asses. Everybodys Got Something to Hide employs the traditional firemans bell in a way that propels the track along perhaps even slightly faster than a real red fire truck could plough through traffic. Helter Skelter seems to have been tailored specifically to my tastes as it has the kind of droning guitar line and steadfast groove that would later become a hallmark of stoner rock groups the world over.
"Happiness is a Warm Gun" starts slowly and then morphs into an edgy rocker before sliding back out the other end into some slick doo-wop action making one of the record's most interesting listens.

Yer Blues has that edgy blues stomp and sounds very much like The Black Keys, and I was on the verge of yelling at my stereo, You plagiarising bastards! when I realised that these guys did it first. Then all of the other similarities started to show themselves. Ob-La-Di Ob-La-Da is basically the blueprint for The Offsprings Why Don't You Get a Job?. Dear Prudence sounds like one of those slow numbers that the Foo Fighters are so fond of peppering their rock records with. Revolution 1 gave rise to bands like Set Fire to Flames and their ilk. Whatever you hear in todays music you have to accept the fact that the Beatles were probably there first, and on no other album is that more obvious than it is on this one, a wild mix of styles jammed together with none of the concept that dominates some of their other records from this era, just good clean musical fun for an hour and a half.

Of course, you cant expect even the most prodigious of bands to maintain for this length of time and occasionally they do falter, not perhaps in the way that other bands would falter dropping enormous embarrassing clangers onto an unsuspecting public or going from pop-punk to avant-garde without the slightest interest in researching the genre but none-the-less there are a couple of throw away numbers on here, but I guess that thats the price you play for letting your drummer loose on a guitar and giving George artistic freedom and four songs to fill up. That is a bit harsh, perhaps, especially considering the fact that up until this point I was convinced that George was my favourite Beatle. But sadly Piggies is as ridiculous as it sounds whilst Long, Long Long is as slow and boring as its title would suggest. Overall, however, the Beatles are hitting all the right notes and the strength of the album is quite remarkable.

What is even more startling is the fact that during some of the recording Ringo had stormed out, Paul was laying down all the tracks for some of his compositions on his own, George was growing a moustache and John was being constantly shadowed by the dark and brooding figure of Yoko Ono who caused a giant, irreparable rift amongst the boys. Friendships were forgotten and egos were inflated to a size more suited for fighting their respective corners. Yet despite this the record flows with a logic and an understanding that would suggest a unified whole. No matter how disparate the songs seem to be in terms of their sound, there is never any question that they should have been included on the final vision. Someone once said that no matter how the Beatles made their decisions, whether they had to physically fight over an issue or whether they pitted their strategic strategies against each other in a head to head game of Battleship, they always made the right choices, and I think that that is very apparent here.

Perhaps even more startling is that this album is so strong yet it contains no number one singles, none of the numbers that radio stations would have favoured playing yet it is still strangely recognisable. I came to The White Album with a limited knowledge of the songs herein but yet I could hold the lyric book in my hand and by the chorus I was confidently singing along as though these were songs I had grown up with (which, for the record, I have not). This is the nut of the Beatles phenomenon I think, that familiarity. Whilst they are known for breaking down new barriers (some would argue dimensions), they never lost sight of the catchy pop hooks that can acquaint a listener with a song and, like a Casanova with a boner, sweet talk you into the sack within a matter of minutes. They were, after all, part of that whole love generation thing. Perhaps that is why they could hate each other so much but still produce a double album of songs which anybody would swear on anybodys grave were born out of love.

The White Album is rated incredibly highly, #1 for 1968 and #15 overall. Is it deserving of such lofty standing? Well, the simple answer is no.

What we have here is 30 tracks spanning over 90 minutes. The band was prolific in their songwriting during this period and some songs recorded during these sessions missed the final cut. Still with 30 tracks, it was never going to be all gold. Even though I do like The Beatles, this album is not nearly as good as many would have you believe.

There are plenty of well known tracks. The only one Id personally rate 5 stars is While My Guitar Gently Weeps. I never get tired of hearing that one. On the next level are Back in the USSR and Dear Prudence, so side one is my personal favourite.

After that, throw a blanket over a myriad of mostly nice enough songs that wont offend anyone. Helter Skelter is an obvious exception. What is an achievement is the incredible variety to be heard here. Not one song sounds like another. Thats especially true of the experimental Revolution 9 which is absolute shite and a complete waste of 8 minutes. Listen to it once and never again.

At this point in my life, The Beatles are more like old friends. I don't spend as much time with them as I once did, maybe because I just know them too well. I know their flaws. I have heard all their stories before. And I've grown tired of all our mutual friends going on about them all the time.

So I can only spend time with them in small doses, and when I do, I usually prefer to do so alone, possibly because our society has turned their music into wallpaper. When I re-visit The Beatles, I want to have a good, meaningful, one on one conversation, and on those occasions when I do, I end up being amazed all over again.

People have long been quibbling about how "the white album" could be improved. Some are turned off by its sheer magnitude and feel it would have made a better single album (Sir George Martin and Ringo Starr among them). Some don't like the brevity of many of the songs or the experimentalism. It's true that not every song here is five star quality, but all of this misses the point a bit.

The reason The Beatles were so great--particularly on this album, in my opinion--is because they attempted things that by all rights should never have worked and succeeded at them: ditching the psychedelic production style of the past year in favor of stripped down minimalism; putting 30 songs on a double album; including song fragments; having all the songs butting up against one other; inserting random link tracks; throwing in an eight minute musique concrte sound collage near the end. Et. al. Other bands have practically tried to make entire careers out of these conventions. It's true that The Beatles perhaps get slightly more credit than they deserve for being innovators, but they did re-write all the rules from time to time, and nowhere more brilliantly than here.

What I have always loved about "the white album" is that it never feels like it's trying too hard. The whole album gives you the impression of sitting around a smoky studio after midnight...particularly on side three (my personal favorite), where The Beatles never rocked harder. "The white album" also has possibly the best overall mood, flow and tone of any Beatles album, to my ears. (It also has my favorite bass guitar sound ever recorded. So there's that.) It's a pop rock album at its heart, but something about it feels gleefully subversive, too. This is something the band had never done before and were never able to duplicate again, as evidenced by the somewhat lackluster Get Back/Let It Be sessions the following year, where boredom, drugs and in-fighting finally trumped inspiration and creativity. "The white album" was lightning in a bottle.

I've often made the case that 1968 was the best year of The Beatles' career. If this album isn't enough to convince you, just take a look at the singles (and b-sides) released this year: "Lady Madonna / The Inner Light," "Hey Jude / Revolution"...not to mention recording "Hey Bulldog" and "Across the Universe." If this was the only year The Beatles ever made music, they'd probably still be regarded as legends.

There have been periods of my life where I've named "the white album" as being my all-time favorite album, and while I can't say that anymore, it is definitely still important and meaningful to me and a totally unique beast in not only the Beatles' canon but the history of rock music.

+35 Vote downBookmarkVote up
It's very rare that I can say I have a single favourite song by a band. In fact, limiting it to bands from whom I've heard more than, say, three albums, I think it's only happened once: here. Well, maybe. On some days, at least, I'd be very tempted to say that The Beatles never made a song as good as "Revolution 9".

No, honestly. I *adore* "Revolution 9" - I wish The Beatles (or anybody really) had made a whole album, or better, a whole bunch of albums, of music like it. It might also be worth mentioning that I think Yoko Ono is maybe better than The Beatles, and John Cage - whose works like "Imaginary Landscape no. 4", "Fontana Mix", "Rozart Mix", etc were probably big influences on "Revolution 9" - is one of my favourite artists.

Avant-garde just doesn't come better than "Revolution 9". The organization of the sound pieces is subtle and brilliant. It's a sprawling, chaotic portrait, and it recalls music made using chance operations - and maybe chance operations were used in its composition - but it also has clear and fascinating structure, on both the mirco- and macro- levels. From beginning to end, there's a deep sense of both tension and melancholy, which are never really resolved, even though the track crescendos at various points. Sounds come and go suddenly, and different pieces are juxtaposed in very strange ways... yet the progression also seems natural and organic. I think this is because of the unqiue way it subverts expectations. Take the intro of the track from 0:30 onwards. There's a distorted pop/rock tune that's clearly building, then at 0:45 this segues neatly into a bombastic classical piece that's clearly setting us up for a climax. The climax comes at 0:50 with the backwards loop - but it's cut to the left channel, it's slower, it's more melancholy. It still retains a kind of inevitability, though - listen to the way the rhythm of backwards loop kinda fits with the rhythm of the classical loop. This is emphasized, just for a second, at about 0:59, when the cymbal from the classical piece appears again, and then again at 1:35, when the backwards loop and the classical loop are played together.

This kind of thing is going on all throughout the track. Strange sources of sound are used, and sounds are played in odd combinations. But they are put together in such a way that the track both conforms, and subverts, conventions and expectations, and often this conformism and subversion is happening at the same time. And while it's doing this, it's also preserving that dual atmosphere of tension and melancholy. Basically, I think it's wrong to just dismiss "Revolution 9" as merely random chaos (not that I have a problem with "random chaos" - as I mentioned, I'm a John Cage fan!). It's far too clever for that. Of course, it's maybe difficult to pick up on that without listening to it many, many times, and I doubt that activity would appeal to a whole lot of people.

Anyway, even without "Revolution 9", this would still be my favourite Beatles album. It's a magical, rambling potpourri of a whole bunch of different genres and moods, crafted into some of most beautiful, inventive compositions The Beatles ever wrote. I'm sure there's enough people saying good things about masterpieces like "Dear Prudence", "Blackbird", "Piggies", "Cry Baby Cry", though. I just wanted to lend some support for "Revolution 9".
